4. Lucretius’ View of Man.

ln man, as in all things else, there is nothing but matter and void. The human organism comprises three distinct parts, the body, the soul or life-principle, and the mind. These originate, develop‚ decline, and perish together, for the mind and soul are inseparably united with each other and with the body.8 The mind is situated in the mid-region ol the breast, while the soul is distributed throughout the form3 but the mind and soul are so closely connected that they may be considered as one nature. They are composed of the finest round atoms,—not of simple elements, however, but ol four separate combinations of atoms mingled together, wind, heat, air, and a subtle, nameless some· thing that makes the fourth.4 Volitional impulse arises in this last element‚ which imparts motion to the heat·portion; thatin turn to the wind, the wind to the air-essence3 thence move· ment is aroused in the organism. The mind and soul of man differ very little from those of animals. Lucretius does not
